WEBVTT

00:00.290 --> 00:03.834
Grace mercy and peace be unto you from our Lord and Savior, Jesus Christ.

00:04.034 --> 00:05.055
Feel join me in a word of prayer.

00:06.416 --> 00:16.947
O God, heavenly Father, as we gather before you this night, we give thanks for the joy of this season and your son, Jesus Christ, who has come to be the light of the world.

00:18.729 --> 00:25.876
We ask tonight that you would lead us to see him as the prophet, priest, and king who has come into this world and indeed into our lives.

00:26.536 --> 00:28.178
Let us see him and welcome him.

00:28.642 --> 00:30.204
and let us come and worship Him.

00:31.085 --> 00:32.067
We pray in Jesus' name.

00:32.868 --> 00:33.128
Amen.

00:33.609 --> 00:34.550
The congregation may be seated.

00:43.002 --> 00:46.126
It is good to hear the voices of some little ones here with us tonight.

00:47.548 --> 00:51.013
Just a couple of years ago, it was my little ones making noise in church.

00:51.854 --> 00:53.757
It's still possible that that could happen too.

00:56.701 --> 00:57.682
Just this last week,

00:58.658 --> 01:07.366
My family was joined to welcome a new baby, my brother and sister-law, Jacob and Sarah, welcomed home their first child.

01:07.967 --> 01:28.466
A child is always a gift and a reminder of God's precious blessings of life and hope for the future we give thanks for the children in our midst, especially as we turn our attention tonight to the Christ child, to God's own son born into this world, born into our midst of the season of Advent, we've been invited to come and watch

01:28.962 --> 01:40.958
and wait, being reminded to be patient for the coming of God's Son and the fulfillment of God's promises in Jesus, the one who has come and the one that we are promised will come again.

01:40.978 --> 01:52.554
We can be reminded as well that he also came just as a child, as a baby, as an infant who also relied upon his own earthly parents to care for him.

01:52.614 --> 01:55.698
He came in all humility

01:56.610 --> 01:59.133
the salvation of the world coming in this humble way.

01:59.473 --> 02:08.264
When we think of a new baby that is born, often we think of words like sweet and tender and mild and innocent.

02:10.086 --> 02:12.629
Those words do apply for a while.

02:15.152 --> 02:18.757
Our wife and I have welcomed home three babies over the last number of years.

02:19.498 --> 02:26.386
And without fail as they grew up, just a little bit from infants onto toddlers, beginning to speak,

02:26.754 --> 02:28.196
and going through the natural stages.

02:29.457 --> 02:36.666
I can remember each one of them over the period of time as they grew, learning words that I'm not sure that we taught them.

02:36.746 --> 02:38.408
Maybe we did without realizing it.

02:38.528 --> 02:40.451
But words like mine.

02:42.473 --> 02:43.294
And I don't want to.

02:43.354 --> 02:48.961
And my personal favorite, first words I can remember Jude stringing together.

02:49.001 --> 02:50.583
No dada.

02:53.827 --> 02:56.370
Doesn't take long for us human beings.

02:57.858 --> 03:03.326
to sort of stray from that veneer of sweet and innocent and mild.

03:04.668 --> 03:08.835
Because we know that from early on, we have that inner desire.

03:08.955 --> 03:20.933
There's that inner will within all of us that we end up, and we can try not to and learn to be careful about it, but we end up putting ourselves before anyone and anything else.

03:22.375 --> 03:27.122
We recklessly know we give thanks tonight that that is not the case with Jesus, this child that we welcome.

03:27.938 --> 03:54.194
The only child born whose innocence would remain true and whose desires were not for himself, who did not put himself first, but rather the needs of his people, the needs of a world he loved, the needs of people he created putting us first, being willing because of that love for us to be put himself into danger and peril.

03:55.394 --> 04:00.640
So we welcome him again this season, the holy one, the righteous Lord, the wonderful counselor, the prince of peace.

04:02.902 --> 04:21.842
I would invite you tonight for just these few minutes to consider as well that if we are really going to welcome him, we can only truly welcome him if we see him in three ways, three titles in addition to those that he has given, three titles and offices that he holds, prophet, priest, and king.

04:23.746 --> 04:25.308
We often call him Jesus Christ.

04:25.388 --> 04:29.893
And sometimes in our minds, the word Christ almost seems like a last name that we're giving to him.

04:30.173 --> 04:31.875
But the word Christ is not a last name.

04:32.536 --> 04:40.444
Rather, it's a title that is rightly given, which means in Greek, Christus, which is Messiah or anointed one.

04:40.485 --> 04:44.149
The beginning of Matthew's gospel opens in this way.

04:44.189 --> 04:52.658
The book of the genealogy of Jesus Christ or Jesus Messiah, anointed one, the son of David, the son of Abraham.

04:53.794 --> 05:04.229
In the Old Testament, there were three offices or positions which someone could hold wherein they would be anointed upon taking that position.

05:04.309 --> 05:16.507
That anointing would come often with oil at the hands of someone else with a promise to serve faithfully and then a word of blessing from God, bringing them into that office, anointing them for it.

05:17.729 --> 05:23.698
The three offices in the Old Testament that are anointed in that way are the offices of prophet, of priest,

05:24.674 --> 05:25.215
and of king.

05:25.275 --> 05:33.666
Now it's hard to believe, thinking about a child, a small infant born into this world.

05:35.228 --> 05:39.134
These are the titles that Jesus does hold and would grow into.

05:39.955 --> 05:42.097
So to consider them briefly each tonight, prophet.

05:43.019 --> 05:45.322
A prophet is one who speaks the truth.

05:47.224 --> 05:54.354
And in the Old Testament, a prophet is one who speaks the truth on God's behalf, coming to the people, especially the people who have forgotten

05:54.498 --> 05:55.639
about the Lord their God.

05:55.699 --> 06:02.986
People who have followed after their own desires, who have taken up other idols, who have chased after things of the world and the prophet comes speaking a word of truth and says, come back.

06:04.468 --> 06:14.157
Return, turn around, remember the Lord your God who has done such great things for you, who has given you all that you have turned back to the Lord your God.

06:16.039 --> 06:19.282
The challenge with the word of a prophet is that it can be hard for us to hear.

06:19.322 --> 06:23.346
It's a word we don't necessarily want to hear.

06:25.698 --> 06:43.978
When I got to my last congregation a number of years ago, as a fairly young pastor still, I decided that part of my ministry during the week, I started writing a midweek email devotional that went out to members of the congregation and it was a way to stay connected with people during the week and also share some news and announcements of the congregation.

06:44.038 --> 06:51.026
So I began writing weekly a devotional that would go out in these emails and it went fairly well at first.

06:51.906 --> 06:58.814
And I can remember a number of people coming and saying that they were thankful for what I had written and encouraging me in the process of writing.

06:59.956 --> 07:02.159
There was one woman in the congregation, a retired teacher.

07:04.341 --> 07:09.508
And she didn't say a whole lot at first, but that first year for Christmas, she gave me two books as presents.

07:11.790 --> 07:13.593
The first one was called nitty gritty grammar.

07:13.613 --> 07:17.938
A guide to clear communication.

07:19.010 --> 07:24.877
And the second one was more nitty gritty grammar, another guy declared communication.

07:26.660 --> 07:29.984
She was very kind and I understood exactly where she was coming from.

07:30.024 --> 07:30.965
I knew what her heart was.

07:31.646 --> 07:32.307
Her name is Karen.

07:32.747 --> 07:39.716
And she was just there to, she was Karen before Karen was Karen.

07:41.138 --> 07:44.722
She was there to truly encourage me.

07:44.994 --> 07:48.718
And that's what she did in her own way, sometimes a little bit more forcefully, but she would read through.

07:48.758 --> 07:50.620
And I knew what was happening for her.

07:50.660 --> 07:59.829
Whenever I spelled a word wrong, whenever I rushed through a sentence, whenever there was a run-on sentence, whenever a comma was in the wrong spot, she would hang on that.

08:00.629 --> 08:02.571
And it would be hard for her to get the rest of the message.

08:04.393 --> 08:06.735
But again, a choice had to be made.

08:08.737 --> 08:10.900
Would I receive her encouragement?

08:12.181 --> 08:13.362
Or would I push back on it?

08:13.730 --> 08:15.433
What I think to myself, well, what difference does it make?

08:15.453 --> 08:17.756
It's not that big of a deal I can just keep doing what I'm doing.

08:17.856 --> 08:20.501
Or should I slow down?

08:20.561 --> 08:24.026
Should I realize where her words are coming from?

08:24.066 --> 08:26.590
A bit of a prophetic and encouraging message.

08:27.131 --> 08:29.535
You're making some mistakes that are unnecessary.

08:29.775 --> 08:31.398
Take a bit more time, slow down.

08:31.498 --> 08:35.124
You can do better at this and maybe occasionally consult a book.

08:38.950 --> 08:41.714
This is the word of the prophet for us as well.

08:42.978 --> 08:54.372
And God's word to us is that we are ultimately sinful people, broken people, people who do chase after our own inner desires, but we are invited to hear God's truth.

08:54.413 --> 09:04.385
This was the purpose of the prophets through scripture to come to call people back with encouragement, with love, mercifully calling God's people back to him.

09:04.425 --> 09:11.314
And now as Jesus comes, John chapter eight tells us, Jesus said to the Jews who had believed in him, if you abide in my word, you are truly my disciples.

09:11.746 --> 09:14.691
And you will know the truth and the truth will set you free.

09:16.514 --> 09:19.038
If you abide in my word, you are truly my disciples.

09:19.078 --> 09:30.897
So as we see Jesus tonight, one, we see him as prophet, the truth of God embodied in a person come into the world where we receive him.

09:32.600 --> 09:33.661
Second, he is a priest.

09:34.783 --> 09:35.985
We give thanks to God for this.

09:36.045 --> 09:37.728
The prophet comes and speaks truth.

09:37.748 --> 09:39.090
He speaks to us.

09:40.610 --> 09:42.933
But the priest comes and he speaks for us.

09:44.316 --> 09:46.218
This is the job of the priest throughout Scripture.

09:47.020 --> 10:04.786
The priest is the intercessor, the one who goes on behalf of the people who are fallen, who are not holy, and goes and mediates to the holy God, speaking the word of the people to the God and bringing prayers of mercy and compassion on behalf of the people.

10:06.370 --> 10:09.475
give thanks for the priest, the one who went and made sacrifices for the people.

10:09.755 --> 10:11.718
And this was the way that it played out in the Old Testament.

10:12.620 --> 10:24.638
God was teaching his people that sin, selfish desire, chasing after our own pride, which brings harm to our neighbor and harm to the world and a broken relationship with our God.

10:27.222 --> 10:30.087
God taught his people that that always results in death.

10:30.768 --> 10:34.834
Sin always results in bloodshed and death, separation from God,

10:35.778 --> 10:40.304
And the end, blood shed is the result.

10:41.625 --> 10:44.509
But what God did for his people then was he allowed for sacrifices.

10:44.569 --> 10:56.183
So the priest, on certain holy days of the year, and especially one holy day of the year, would take animals who would stand in the place of the people so that the people's blood wouldn't have to be shed so that they could go on with their lives and live in the presence of God.

10:56.564 --> 11:05.074
The priest would take an animal of various different kinds, a sheep or a lamb, sometimes a cow or a bull.

11:06.018 --> 11:12.707
And the priest would go into the temple, into the holy place, and would make a sacrifice on behalf of the people the animal would take the punishment of sin.

11:15.632 --> 11:21.620
It's hard to believe, and I know that Mary and Joseph couldn't understand all of this at the beginning, but this is exactly why Christ came.

11:23.603 --> 11:31.634
He becomes the priest for all, a priest higher than the high priest of the Old Testament.

11:32.386 --> 11:50.006
A priest who would ultimately not give an animal but himself, a priest who would be broken, a priest who would willingly go to the cross that his blood would be shed, that he would be placed there, that he would become the sacrifice, finally, eternally, so that the people could be spared.

11:50.927 --> 11:53.089
This is why he comes into the world.

11:53.229 --> 12:01.138
In this way, we give thanks for the priest who comes as the intercessor for us, as the mediator who goes on our behalf to God.

12:02.402 --> 12:04.124
But finally, he is also the king.

12:04.164 --> 12:16.256
If Jesus had come and had taught and had worked miracles and had led his people to follow him and then had gone to the cross and sacrificed himself, that would have been so much.

12:17.417 --> 12:19.099
That would have been a great example.

12:19.579 --> 12:27.827
He would have taken our sins upon himself there, but if he had stayed on the cross, it would not have been everything, at least not everything that we need because there is one more.

12:29.369 --> 12:30.450
There's one more deep,

12:30.530 --> 12:39.444
need of our lives and that is to be able to overcome the greatest threat of all which is finally death itself.

12:42.169 --> 12:43.330
Jesus didn't stay on the cross.

12:43.370 --> 12:53.206
He rose on the third day from the grave to show that he has victory there as well, to show that he has power even over this greatest foe that we all face which is death.

12:56.491 --> 12:58.194
I was saddened to read yesterday

12:59.234 --> 13:01.718
a post written on social media by former U.S.

13:01.738 --> 13:03.882
Senator from Nebraska, Ben Sasse.

13:03.902 --> 13:09.671
He served from 2015 to 2023, and then served as the president of the University of Florida since retired from that post.

13:10.813 --> 13:14.179
And he wrote on social media, this is a tough note to write, friends.

13:15.100 --> 13:25.778
But since a bunch of you have started to suspect something I'll cut to the chase, last week I was diagnosed with metastasized stage four pancreatic cancer, and I am going to die.

13:26.978 --> 13:28.841
Advanced pancreatic is nasty stuff.

13:28.881 --> 13:30.824
It's a death sentence.

13:30.844 --> 13:35.090
But I already had a death sentence before last week too.

13:36.552 --> 13:37.113
We all do.

13:39.156 --> 13:42.742
Now, share a little bit more of what he wrote in just a moment.

13:44.064 --> 13:45.386
But this is the reality of the season.

13:45.426 --> 13:53.458
I know this is heavy material for a Christmas Eve sermon because we are caught up in the season and all the joy that does come with the season

13:53.666 --> 14:05.600
And especially when children are around the joy of their faces, the expectation, the looking forward, the time with family and the baking and the cooking and the eating too much and all of the things that we fit into this season.

14:05.640 --> 14:06.521
And there is a joy.

14:08.324 --> 14:16.634
But the reality of this world is that there is also a pain and a sadness and a difficulty and problems.

14:17.334 --> 14:23.602
And while we may be able to step away from this, from those things for a little while and I hope and pray that we do and can,

14:24.290 --> 14:27.457
We know that they are still not too far away.

14:30.142 --> 14:36.836
Ben Sasse went to write on in his post, there's not a good time to tell your people that you're now marching to the beat of a faster drummer.

14:37.558 --> 14:39.261
But the season of Advent isn't the worst.

14:40.224 --> 14:45.234
As a Christian, the weeks running up to Christmas are a time to orient our hearts towards the hope of what is to come.

14:45.634 --> 14:54.150
Not an abstract hope in fanciful human goodness, not hope in vague, hallmark, sappy spirituality, not a bootstrapped hope in our own strength.

14:55.212 --> 14:58.839
What foolishness is the evaporating muscle that I once prided myself in.

14:58.900 --> 15:03.448
Nope, we often lazily say hope when what we mean is optimism.

15:03.889 --> 15:08.498
To be clear optimism is great, and it's absolutely necessary, but it's insufficient.

15:08.706 --> 15:16.534
It's not the kind of thing that's gonna hold you up when you tell your daughters you're not going to be there to walk them down the aisle, nor telling your mom and pops that they're gonna bury their son.

15:17.315 --> 15:20.218
But a life well lived demands more reality, stiffer stuff.

15:21.059 --> 15:31.810
That's why during Advent, even while still walking in darkness, we shout our hope, often properly with a gravelly voice, soldiering through tears.

15:32.991 --> 15:35.474
I'll have more to say, I'm not going down without a fight.

15:35.618 --> 15:42.626
One sub-part of God's grace is found in the jaw-dropping advances science has made these past few years in immunotherapy and more.

15:43.226 --> 15:44.387
Death and dying aren't the same.

15:44.488 --> 15:46.710
The process of dying is still something to be lived.

15:47.831 --> 15:54.598
We're zealously embracing a lot of gallows humor in our house, and I've pledged to do my part to run through the irreverent tape.

15:55.319 --> 16:01.085
But for now as our family faces the reality of treatments, and more importantly as we celebrate Christmas, we wish you peace.

16:02.427 --> 16:05.330
The people walking in darkness have seen a great light.

16:06.338 --> 16:11.866
On those living in the land of deep darkness, a light has dawned for to us a sun is given."

16:13.369 --> 16:14.230
Isaiah chapter 9.

16:14.270 --> 16:22.763
I'm very sorry and saddened that Ben had to write these words, but I certainly couldn't have said it better.

16:22.803 --> 16:28.992
The hope that we hold on to this season is not optimism, it is trust.

16:30.475 --> 16:35.442
It's not an idea or a theory, but a person that we are meant to see

16:35.970 --> 16:54.763
and to welcome and to know and to understand as prophet, as priest, and as king, the fullness of God come to dwell in a human person, the love of God come down to earth, to rescue us from that which holds us away from our God, rescuing us even from death itself.

16:56.486 --> 16:58.489
So let us see him again this season.

16:59.531 --> 17:01.234
Come and study and find him.

17:01.506 --> 17:04.591
See his goodness, understand his mercy and his compassion.

17:04.951 --> 17:10.300
See the ways that he's taken our sins upon his shoulders, that he willingly went to the cross to forgive our sins.

17:10.620 --> 17:13.064
This is God's love revealed for us.

17:14.626 --> 17:26.865
Our response is thankfulness and worship and sharing this good news of mercy with one another and seeking to live in his pattern throughout our lives.

17:28.007 --> 17:28.307
Amen.

17:28.508 --> 17:30.130
And once again, if you'll join me in a word of prayer,

17:32.194 --> 17:36.760
Lord God, as we gather before you this evening, we give thanks for your mercies, which are new every day.

17:36.820 --> 17:55.986
We know as well that during this season, though it is a season of joy and hope and light, we still carry with us the burden of the challenges of this world, be that sickness or grief or mourning or the knowledge of very real needs in the world around us, those who do not have enough in this life.

17:56.930 --> 18:06.647
Lord, we place these things in your hands, and we ask that you would lead us once again to see your son, Jesus Christ, the very hope of the world, the light of our lives, the Savior who has come and who will come again.

18:06.687 --> 18:11.796
Let us receive him this night as our prophet, our priest, and our king.

18:12.777 --> 18:13.138
Amen.

